SUBSTITUTE FOR
HOUSE BILL NO. 4283
A bill to amend 2008 PA 295, entitled
"Clean and renewable energy and energy waste reduction act,"
by amending sections 28, 29, and 32 (MCL 460.1028, 460.1029, and
460.1032), sections 28 and 29 as amended and section 32 as added by
2023 PA 235, and by adding section 34.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF MICHIGAN ENACT:
1 Sec. 28. (1) An electric provider shall achieve a renewable
2 energy credit portfolio of at least the following:
3 (a) Through 2029, 15%.
4 (b) In 2030 through 2034, 50%.
5 (c) In 2035 and each year thereafter, 60%.
6 (2) An electric provider's renewable energy credit portfolio
7 shall be calculated as follows:
TMV H02140'25 (H-1) gx2hk3

2
1 (a) Determine the number of renewable energy credits used to
2 comply with this subpart during the applicable year.
3 (b) Divide by 1 of the following at the option of the electric
4 provider as specified in its renewable energy plan:
5 (i) The number of weather normalized megawatt hours of
6 electricity sold by the electric provider during the previous year
7 to retail customers in this state, less the amount of sales
8 attributable to customers participating in an electric provider's
9 voluntary green pricing program under section 61 and the outflow
10 from customers participating in the distributed generation program
11 under section 173 for that year.
12 (ii) The average number of megawatt hours of electricity sold
13 by the electric provider annually during the previous 3 years to
14 retail customers in this state, less the amount of sales
15 attributable to customers participating in an electric provider's
16 voluntary green pricing program under section 61 and the outflow
17 from customers participating in the distributed generation program
18 under section 173 for that year.
19 (c) Multiply the quotient under subdivision (b) by 100.
20 (3) Notwithstanding subsection (1) and subject to subsection
21 (4), in any year a cooperative electric provider or a multistate
22 electric provider may calculate its maximum renewable energy credit
23 portfolio requirement as follows:
24 (a) Determine the number of megawatt hours of electricity sold
25 by the electric provider to retail customers in this state using
26 the option the electric provider selected under subsection (2)(b).
27 (b) Subtract the number of megawatt hours of nuclear energy
28 that the electric provider obtained from a system located in this
29 state that the electric provider owned or from which the electric
TMV H02140'25 (H-1) gx2hk3

3
1 provider had contracted to receive nuclear energy on or before
2 January 1, 2024.
3 (4) An electric provider described in subsection (3) is
4 required to achieve a renewable energy credit portfolio equal only
5 to the electric provider's maximum renewable energy credit
6 portfolio requirement if the electric provider's maximum renewable
7 energy credit portfolio requirement is less than the number of
8 renewable energy credits required to comply with the applicable
9 standard in subsection (1). If the electric provider is a
10 multistate electric provider, and the electric provider's maximum
11 renewable energy credit portfolio requirement is less than the
12 number of renewable energy credits required to comply with the
13 applicable standard in subsection (1), then the electric provider
14 is required to achieve a renewable energy credit portfolio equal
15 only to the electric provider's maximum renewable energy credit
16 portfolio requirement if all of the following requirements are met:
17 (a) The electric provider's electricity generation systems
18 located within this state produce energy exceeding the electric
19 provider's electricity sales in this state.
20 (b) All of the electric provider's electricity generation
21 systems located within this state are clean energy systems.
22 (c) All of the renewable energy credits generated in this
23 state are used by the electric provider toward compliance to comply
24 with the renewable energy credit portfolio requirement, as
25 calculated under subsection (2).
26 (d) Renewable energy and clean energy generated in this state
27 equal to or exceeding the provider's electricity sales in this
28 state are not used by the provider or any other provider to comply
29 with any similar standards.
